headline: Tyson Expects Pressure on Cattle Herds for Foreseeable Future
summary: U.S. cattle herds may be smaller for the foreseeable future as ranchers show few signs of building up the nation’s livestock supply, said executives from Tyson Foods, America’s largest meat supplier.  Last week the U.S. Agriculture Department said the cattle herd was at its lowest level since 1951.  “The data that we see indicates an ultimately smaller herd,” Tyson Chief Operating Officer Devin Cole said on a call with analysts.

headline: Cattle Supply Crunch Weighs on Profit at Tyson Foods
summary: Tyson Foods said quarterly profit fell, as the lowest U.S. cattle supply in 75 years continues to squeeze meatpackers.  Arkansas-based Tyson and rivals are facing a cattle shortage on American pastures, driving beef prices to record levels.  That was down 76% from a year ago and lower than Wall Street analysts expected, according to FactSet.
